Have you ever stared at a LeetCode problem, completely blanked out, and wished you had a Senior Engineer sitting next to you? Someone to guide you through the logic, write the initial boilerplate, explain the time complexity, and instantly optimize your brute-force approach?
I decided to build exactly that.
In this deep dive, I’ll walk you through how I built a production-grade LeetCode AI Assistant Chrome Extension. This isn’t just a basic wrapper around an API. It is an autonomous tool powered by Google’s Gemini 3.5 Flash model and a FastAPI backend that literally breaks out of Chrome’s security sandbox, injects the AI-generated code directly into LeetCode’s Monaco editor, and clicks the “Submit” button for you.
Here is an unfiltered look at the architecture, the technical hurdles (like battling Content Security Policies), and how you can architect a highly extensible system like this yourself.

🏗️ The Architecture: Why Two Tiers?
The easiest (and worst) way to build an AI Chrome Extension is to throw an API key directly into your frontend Javascript and make network calls from the browser. Don’t do this. It exposes your keys, creates CORS nightmares, and makes your extension bloated and difficult to maintain.
To keep the application highly scalable, secure, and adherent to SOLID principles, I split the project into two distinct environments.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

1. The Python Backend (FastAPI + Strategy Pattern)
The core engine of this project is a lightweight, blazing-fast Python backend built with FastAPI.
I knew that AI models are evolving rapidly. Today it’s Gemini, tomorrow it might be a new OpenAI model. To ensure the backend didn’t become a tangled mess of if/else statements, I leveraged Object-Oriented Programming and the Strategy Pattern.
I created an abstract base class called LLMProvider:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethodclass LLMProvider(ABC):
def _parse_json(self, text: str) -> dict:
# Global markdown stripping and JSON formatting
pass
@abstractmethod
def generate_solution(self, problem_details: dict) ->
dict:
pass
By pushing the repetitive JSON-parsing and error-handling boilerplate into this base class, every subsequent AI provider class becomes incredibly lightweight.
The routing is handled by a simple dictionary router in endpoints.py:
PROVIDERS = {
"gemini": GeminiProvider()
}@router.post("/generate")
async def generate_solution(request: schemas.GenerateRequest):
result = get_llm_provider(request.model).generate_solution(request.problem.dict())
return schemas.GenerateResponse(**result)
This decoupled design means the backend dynamically receives the scraped LeetCode problem description, constructs a highly specific prompt template, formats the response cleanly, and fires it back to the client.
2. The Chrome Extension (Manifest V3)
The frontend UI is a sleek, glassmorphic panel built strictly with Vanilla JS and CSS to keep the extension footprint as small as possible.
Because we use Manifest V3, we rely heavily on a background.js Service Worker. This service worker acts as a proxy: when the user clicks "Generate", the UI (popup.js) sends a message to background.js, which securely forwards the payload to the local FastAPI backend, circumventing any Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) issues on LeetCode's domain.

🧠 Prompt Engineering for Code Generation
An LLM is only as good as the prompt you feed it. To ensure the AI consistently returns valid, insertable code, the backend formats the scraped LeetCode problem into a strict JSON-demanding prompt:
You are an expert competitive programmer. Solve the following LeetCode problem.
Title: {title}
Difficulty: {difficulty}
Description: {description}Return your response strictly as a JSON object with the following keys:
- "code": The exact python code to insert.
- "explanation": A brief explanation of the logic.
- "complexity": Time and Space complexity.
By forcing a strict JSON schema, the backend _parse_json method can safely parse the response and guarantee that the extension frontend receives a predictable data structure every single time, avoiding cases where the AI starts "chatting" instead of coding.

🚧 The Boss Fight: LeetCode’s Content Security Policy
Getting an AI to generate code is relatively straightforward. Getting that code into the LeetCode editor autonomously is brutally hard.
Modern LeetCode heavily guards its internal window.monaco editor state.
Attempt 1: Simulated Keystrokes I initially tried to physically locate the hidden <textarea> inside the Monaco editor DOM and simulate a Paste command using document.execCommand('insertText'). The problem? If your Chrome Extension popup is open, the popup steals window focus. Without strict focus on the LeetCode tab, simulated keyboard events silently die into the void.
Attempt 2: Inline Script Injection I then tried to inject an inline <script> tag into the DOM to directly execute Javascript in the main page context and call window.monaco.editor.getModels()[0].setValue(). The problem? LeetCode’s extremely strict Content Security Policy (CSP) actively blocked and destroyed any inline scripts I injected.
The Ultimate Solution: Manifest V3 chrome.scripting
To bypass the CSP and securely access the memory state of the Monaco editor, I realized I needed to reach through the browser’s sandbox natively.
Using the new Manifest V3 scripting API, I executed my injection code natively in the MAIN world, originating the call from the popup itself rather than the content script:
function insertCodeAndSubmit(tabId, generatedCode) {
chrome.scripting.executeScript({
target: { tabId: tabId },
world: "MAIN", // This completely bypasses LeetCode's CSP!
func: (injectedCode) => {
// Natively interact with the active Monaco instance memory
if (window.monaco && window.monaco.editor) {
const editors = window.monaco.editor.getEditors();
if (editors.length > 0) {
editors[0].setValue(injectedCode);
}
}
},
args: [generatedCode]
}, () => {
// After injection, tell the content script to click the submit button
chrome.tabs.sendMessage(tabId, { action: "SUBMIT_CODE" });
});
}Because this script runs natively via the Chrome Extension engine in the main execution environment rather than as a hacky injected HTML tag, LeetCode’s CSP rules do not apply. The code drops instantly into the active editor, bypassing the need for simulated keyboard strokes entirely.

🚀 The Finishing Touch: Auto-Submit
What good is an autonomous AI if you still have to manually click buttons? I wired the extension to automatically hunt down the “Submit” button exactly 500ms after the code drops into the editor (giving the React UI time to register the state change).
(Insert your real screenshot of a successful LeetCode submission here, showing the “Accepted” state!)
Because LeetCode frequently updates their UI frameworks and obfuscates class names, I wrote a highly robust fallback heuristic in content.js:
function submitCodeOnLeetCode() {
const selectors = [
'[data-e2e-locator="console-submit-button"]',
'[data-layout-path="/ts0/vb/be0"] button',
'.submit__2_60'
]; let submitBtn = null;
for (const sel of selectors) {
submitBtn = document.querySelector(sel);
if (submitBtn) break;
}
// Fallback: search all buttons for the exact text "Submit"
if (!submitBtn) {
const buttons = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('button'));
submitBtn = buttons.find(b => b.textContent.trim() === 'Submit');
}
if (submitBtn) submitBtn.click();
}
This ensures that even if LeetCode radically changes their frontend layout tomorrow, the extension will still find the submit button by physically iterating over the DOM text nodes.

🎯 Final Thoughts
Building this extension was an absolute masterclass in deeply understanding browser security models, Manifest V3 Service Workers, and writing robust, DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) backend Python code.
The resulting application is entirely modular. If a new, smarter LLM drops tomorrow, I only have to write a few lines of code to instantiate it in my backend, and the extension instantly inherits its capabilities.
If you want to read the code, poke around the architecture, or use it for your own daily LeetCode grind, the entire project is open-source!
